		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [4.43]</nobr><br><br><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>*this is the original post that I wrote sometime back on this subject.&nbsp;&nbsp;My apologies to those who have already read this*<br><br>******************************************************************************************************<br><br><br>Ah, the temptation of "quick and easy" levels... <br><br>Therein lies the danger-- you move up quickly through the ranks with illgotten experience, but you suffer from "post-experiencial trauma" or otherwise commonly known as getting yourself dead. <br><br>Mobs that ordinarily would be simple for you to slaughter open a can of Whoopass on your monkey and use him as a birthday pinata for Dornn. <br><br>Repent, young monkey, from your sins and return to the work ethic that our class requires of its' acolytes. Find a good well equiped group where you are the 5th or 6th man and take on yellows and reds to polish those neglected combat skills. Forsake the lure of powerleveling and quicker delays and harder hits from weapons and return to your roots-- your hands and the slow but steady increase of your skills. <br><br><br>To illustrate my point let me tell you of a duel I engaged in where my opponent had powerleveled three levels higher than me in my late 20's. We were similarly equipped with full sets of cured silk and minor stat increasing items. We both were fighting with batons, I had one, he had two. Three times during the fight I intimidated him and twice I disarmed him. <br><br>Needless to say I demolished him. <br><br>Devastated him. <br><br>Crushed him. <br><br>And thoroughly humiliated him. <br><br>Without his baton he had no offense. His defensive skills were sorely lacking. His specials were worthless. And to top it all off he was so far into his character's life it would be near to impossible to regain those skills that I had been improving since Day One. <br><br>Verant has designed the monkey class to be a more "complete" class than any other. For a monk to be effective in pulling, splitting, and killing ALL of his skills must be polished. <br><br>If you remain with the monkey class until the point at which your hand-to-hand catches up with your 1 hand blunt skill you should equip the baton in your primary hand and leave your other hand free to punch your opponents. Both skills will rise and max out before you level up. This will bring equilbrium back into your combat skills. <br><br>Finally, there is good news-- even though you are fairly far along you are young enough yet to recover and bring those skills back up. Keep working at it! <br><br>Good luck, young monkey! </p><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>first to 10k in a manner other than shameless spamming on the Last thread gets to be the goldenboy. oh wait, that could have been you...if you weren't a damned post whore, you @#%^in' wanker. --Skeeter</td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >0 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td>
